df_output = pd.Series(test_df[0:4], index=['Test Statistic', 'p-value', 'Lags Used', 'Number of Observations'])

def plot_rolling_stats(series, window=12, title=None):
    """
    Plot rolling statistics for time series data with optimizations for large datasets.
    
    Parameters:
        series (pd.Series): Time series data
        window (int): Rolling window size
        title (str): Optional plot title
    """
    # Calculate rolling statistics
    rolling_mean = series.rolling(window).mean()
    rolling_std = series.rolling(window).std()
    
    # Create figure with constrained layout
    fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(12, 5), layout='constrained')
    
    # Plot data with optimized parameters
    ax.plot(series, label='Original', linewidth=0.5, alpha=0.7)
    ax.plot(rolling_mean, label=f'Rolling Mean (window={window})', color='red', linewidth=1.2)
    ax.plot(rolling_std, label=f'Rolling Std (window={window})', color='green', linewidth=1.2)
    
    # Add labels and legend
    ax.set_title(title or "Rolling Statistics")
    ax.set_xlabel('Year')
    ax.set_ylabel('Temperature (C)')
    ax.legend()
    ax.grid(True, linestyle='--', alpha=0.6)
    
    plt.show()

plot_rolling_stats(monthly_temp, window=12)  # Monthly data
plot_rolling_stats(yearly_temp, window=5)    # Yearly data

yearly_temp = glob_temp['AverageTemperature'].resample('Y').mean().dropna()

model = auto_arima(
    yearly_temp,
    start_p=1, max_p=3,  # AR terms
    start_q=1, max_q=3,  # MA terms
    d=1,                 # Differencing (test with `test='adf'`)
    seasonal=False,      # No seasonality for yearly data
    m=1,                # No seasonal cycle
    trend='c',           # Constant only (optional)
    test='adf',          # Validate stationarity
    trace=True,
    stepwise=True,
    suppress_warnings=True
)
print(model.summary())

4.2 SARIMA Model¶
In [52]:
# Optimized SARIMA model for yearly temperature data
sarima_model = auto_arima(
    yearly_temp,
    # Non-seasonal parameters
    start_p=1, max_p=3,  # AR order
    start_q=1, max_q=3,  # MA order
    d=None,              # Let auto_arima determine differencing (better than forcing d=1)
    # Seasonal parameters (disabled for yearly data)
    seasonal=False,      # Critical - no seasonality in yearly aggregates
    m=1,                # Must be 1 when seasonal=False
    # Trend specification
    trend='c',          # Just constant (not 'ct') since differencing handles trends
    # Optimization settings
    test='adf',         # Validate stationarity
    trace=True,
    stepwise=True,
    suppress_warnings=True,
    error_action='ignore',
    # Explicitly disable seasonal search
    start_P=0, max_P=0,
    start_Q=0, max_Q=0
)

print(sarima_model.summary())

from statsmodels.tsa.statespace.sarimax import SARIMAX
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import pandas as pd

# Assume `yearly_temp` is already indexed by year and cleaned
# Train SARIMA model
model = SARIMAX(yearly_temp, order=(1,1,1), seasonal_order=(1,1,1,12))
results = model.fit()

# Forecast next 10 years
forecast = results.get_forecast(steps=10)
forecast_index = pd.date_range(start='2022', periods=10, freq='Y')
forecast_mean = forecast.predicted_mean
conf_int = forecast.conf_int()

# Plot
plt.figure(figsize=(10,6))
plt.plot(yearly_temp, label='Observed')
plt.plot(forecast_index, forecast_mean, label='Forecast', color='orange')
plt.fill_between(forecast_index, conf_int.iloc[:, 0], conf_int.iloc[:, 1], color='orange', alpha=0.2)
plt.title("Temperature Forecast (20222032)")
plt.xlabel("Year")
plt.ylabel("Average Temperature (C)")
plt.legend()
plt.grid(True)
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()
